  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "A gouache on paper (272 x 360 mm) by **Cornelis Troost** (Amsterdam, 1696 – Amsterdam, 1750), dated **1742**, depicting a crowd assembled before the inn **'t Bokje** in the **Haarlemmerhout** to witness an elaborate prank orchestrated by writer-satirist **Jacob Campo Weyerman** (1677–1747) and associates in 1739: a figure exposes painted buttocks arranged to mimic a face in a first-floor window, with blackened trumpeters and mock-ceremonial fanfare, parodying public fascination with the Moroccan ambassador. This is one of at least four treatments Troost made of this subject. Acquired by Teylers in **1780 for 100 guilders** — a considerable sum for a drawing at the time. Designated one of Teylers' **50 Topstukken**.",
